Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(6 inline comments)

It's good to see a lot of new unit tests for this, but I've got a few nits.

The biggest thing that stood out to me was the tests at the the bottom of the commit which are just testing simple (in one case a single line) internal helper functions. To me this seems a bit unnecessary, these methods are simple and you would get a lot of errors elsewhere if they weren't working. I just don't feel there is any value in testing them.

Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

Thanks for reviewing Matthew.

I think it's a fair point about the value of testing helper methods, on further inspection I don't see much other evidence of it in other glance tests.  I've left the test for get_status_code() in as it's not marked with an underscore, so I see no harm in sanity checking it.

Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)

@Paul in python2.6 you can use contextlib.nested:

from contextlib import nested

with nested(A(), B(), C()) as (X, Y, Z):
    ...

In python 2.7 and 3 you can use

with A() as X, B() as Y, C() as Z:
    ...

Patch Set 5:

Mark, thanks for your feedback.

I'm a little confused as to why those tests are failing for you.

I think your errors seem valid, as get_connect_kwargs is indeed calling os.environ.get('GLANCE_CLIENT_CA_FILE') in those cases.  However, I'm also *not* calling self.mock.VerifyAll() in those cases as I wasn't as concerned about the order of method calls for those tests as I was that the assertions passed.

If anyone has any insight on this I'd really appreciate it, otherwise I can push up a new PS that includes the missing checks that seem to be causing the errors Mark pasted.
